        <section class="main-section" id="HTML_and_CSS">
            <header>
                <h2>HTML and CSS</h2>
            </header>
            <p>This section covers the basics of HTML and CSS.</p>
            <p>HTML (Hypertext Markup Language) is the standard language for creating web pages.</p>
            <p>CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) is used for styling web pages.</p>
            <code>&lt;html&gt;</code>
            <code>&lt;head&gt;</code>
            <code>&lt;style&gt;</code>
            <p>HTML provides the structure, while CSS provides the design.</p>
            <ul>
                <li>HTML is used for structuring content.</li>
                <li>CSS is used for styling the content.</li>
                <li>HTML tags define the structure of a webpage.</li>
                <li>CSS can be inline, internal, or external.</li>
                <li>CSS is essential for responsive web design.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="main-section" id="JavaScript_and_Java">
            <header>
                <h2>JavaScript and Java</h2>
            </header>
            <p>JavaScript is a programming language used for creating dynamic content on websites.</p>
            <p>Java is a general-purpose programming language often used for backend development.</p>
            <code>let x = 5;</code>
            <code>console.log(x);</code>
            <code>public class HelloWorld {}</code>
            <p>JavaScript interacts with the HTML DOM, while Java is used for building standalone applications.</p>
            <ul>
                <li>JavaScript is commonly used for frontend development.</li>
                <li>Java is often used for enterprise applications.</li>
                <li>JavaScript can be run directly in the browser.</li>
                <li>Java is compiled into bytecode.</li>
                <li>Both Java and JavaScript have similar syntax but are used for different purposes.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="main-section" id="API_Development">
            <header>
                <h2>API Development</h2>
            </header>
            <p>An API (Application Programming Interface) allows different software systems to communicate with each other.</p>
            <p>REST APIs use HTTP requests for communication.</p>
            <code>GET /users</code>
            <code>POST /users</code>
            <code>PATCH /users/{id}</code>
            <p>API documentation is crucial for developers to understand how to interact with the API.</p>
            <ul>
                <li>REST is the most common architectural style for APIs.</li>
                <li>AP
 <li>APIs use standard HTTP methods like GET, POST, and PUT.</li>
                <li>API responses are often in JSON format.</li>
                <li>Authentication and authorization are important for securing APIs.</li>
                <li>API versioning ensures backward compatibility.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="main-section" id="Version_Control">
            <header>
                <h2>Version Control</h2>
            </header>
            <p>Version control is a system that allows developers to track changes to code over time.</p>
            <p>Git is the most popular version control system used today.</p>
            <code>git init</code>
            <code>git add .</code>
            <code>git commit -m "Initial commit"</code>
            <p>Version control helps teams collaborate more effectively on code.</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Git is distributed, meaning each developer has a full copy of the repository.</li>
                <li>Branches in Git allow for isolated development.</li>
                <li>GitHub is a popular platform for hosting Git repositories.</li>
                <li>Version control systems help prevent loss of code.</li>
                <li>Merge conflicts occur when different changes are made to the same code.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

         <section class="main-section" id="Software_Engineering_Principles">
            <header>
                <h2>Software Engineering Principles</h2>
            </header>
            <p>Software engineering principles help developers write efficient, maintainable, and reliable code.</p>
            <p>Principles such as DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) and SOLID are widely adopted in the industry.</p>
            <code>if (x == y) {}</code>
            <code>public class MyClass {}</code>
            <code>for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {}</code>
            <p>These principles ensure that code is modular, reusable, and easy to maintain.</p>
            <ul>
                <li>DRY: Avoid code duplication.</li>
                <li>SOLID: A set of principles for object-oriented design.</li>
                <li>Code should be easy to read and understand.</li>
                <li>Tests should be written to verify the correctness of code.</li>
                <li>Code should be decoupled to promote flexibility.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>
